[[File:Aspie for freedom.png|thumb|236px<!--(approx Sidebar/Infobox)-->|Aspies for Freedom logo]] {{Autism rights movement |orgs}}
'''Aspies For Freedom''' ('''AFF''') is a solidarity and campaigning group that aimed at raising public awareness of the [[autism rights movement]]. The aim of Aspies For Freedom is to educate the public that the autism spectrum is not always a [[disability]], and that there are advantages as well as disadvantages.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9RrshCudnIAC&lpg=PA82&dq=%22aspies%20for%20freedom%22&pg=PA82#v=onepage&q=%22aspies%20for%20freedom%22&f=false|title=Autism Spectrum Disorders: A Reference Handbook|last=Bernier|first=Raphael|last2=Gerdts|first2=Jennifer|publisher=ABC-CLIO|year=2010|isbn=9781598843347|location=|pages=82}}</ref> For this purpose, the group organizes an annual [[Autistic Pride Day]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Autistic Licence |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,589-1960650,00.html |work=Times Online |date=31 December 2005 |accessdate=8 November 2007 |location=London |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060103050400/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0%2C%2C589-1960650%2C00.html |archivedate=January 3, 2006 }}</ref> AFF provides support for the autistic community and protests attempts to cure autism.<ref name=":0" />
Established in 2004 by Amy and Gareth Nelson, AFF has received coverage from publications such as ''[[New Scientist]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite news |last=Trivedi |first=Bijal |title=Autistic and proud of it |date=18 June 2005 |work=New Scientist |location= London |url= https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg18625041.500.html |accessdate=8 November 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070815184818/http://www.newscientist.com/article/mg18625041.500.html |archivedate= 15 August 2007}}</ref> As of August 2007, ''[[The Guardian]]'' estimated the group's membership at 20,000.<ref name=":0">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2007/aug/07/health.medicineandhealth|title=G2: 'It is not a disease, it is a way of life'|last=Saner|first=Emine|date=12 August 2007|work=The Guardian|location=London|page=12}}</ref> Rob Crossan, writing for the BBC, mentioned their belief that higher functioning autistics are often in possession of extraordinary talents in the fields of mathematics, memory, music or arts.<ref name="OuchAspies">{{cite web |last=Crossan |first=Rob|title=Ouch Q&A #19: Aspies |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/ouch/fact/ouch_q_a_19_aspies.shtml |work=Ouch! It's a disability thing |publisher=BBC |accessdate=12 June 2010}}</ref>
==Activism== Gareth Nelson, the founder of Aspies for Freedom, has made internet parodies of [[Autism Speaks]], saying that they were silencing opposing views.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Biever|first=Celeste|date=2008-02-02|title=Dispute rages over who speaks for autistic people|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0262407908602596|journal=New Scientist|volume=197|issue=2641|pages=9|doi=10.1016/S0262-4079(08)60259-6}}</ref> Aspies For Freedom petitioned the [[United Nations]] in 2004 to have members of the autistic community recognised as a [[Autistic community#Declaration from the autism community|minority status group]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AY5mlqWXx5QC&lpg=PA279&dq=%22aspies%20for%20freedom%22&pg=PA279#v=onepage&q=%22aspies%20for%20freedom%22&f=false|title=Sex and Disability|last=Groner|first=Rachael|publisher=Duke University Press|year=2012|isbn=978-0822351542|editor-last=McRuer|editor-first=Robert|location=|pages=279|chapter=Sex As Spock|editor-last2=Mollow|editor-first2=Anna}}</ref> A statement was released from the group titled 'Declaration of the autism community'. This article detailed reasons for seeking such official recognition from the [[United Nations]] and the work towards achieving this.<ref name=UN>{{cite press release |url= http://www.prweb.com/releases/2004/11/prweb179444.htm |title=Declaration From the Autism Community That They Are a Minority Group |date =18 November 2004 |publisher=PRWeb, Press Release Newswire |accessdate=7 November 2007}}</ref> AFF was cited by ''[[The Guardian]]'' as a resource for autism employment assistance.<ref>{{cite news |date=17 October 2009 |title= Work: Giving autistic people access to work |page=2 |work=The Guardian |location= London}}</ref> Gareth Nelson and Aspies for Freedom have spoken out against prenatal [[genetic testing]] for [[autism spectrum disorders]], portraying autism as a difference as opposed to a disability.<ref name=":0" /><ref name="GatesQuestion">{{cite web|last=Caplan|first=Arthur|title=Would you have allowed Bill Gates to be born? Advances in prenatal genetic testing pose tough questions|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/7899821/|publisher=MSNBC|accessdate=12 June 2010}}</ref>
